To clean up an HTML document by removing unnecessary tags, you can use JavaScript to manipulate the DOM and strip out specific elements you don't need. Below is a simple JavaScript function that you can run in a browser environment to clean up the HTML code. This example assumes you want to remove certain elements while keeping the structure intact. You can adjust the function to target specific tags or classes as needed.

Here's a basic example of a JavaScript function to remove unnecessary tags:

```javascript
function cleanHTML() {
    // Get the root element (in this case, the body)
    const body = document.body;

    // Remove unnecessary tags by selecting them and removing them
    const tagsToRemove = ['header', 'footer']; // Add any tags you want to remove to this array

    tagsToRemove.forEach(tag => {
        const elements = body.getElementsByTagName(tag);
        while (elements[0]) {
            elements[0].parentNode.removeChild(elements[0]);
        }
    });

    // You can also remove elements by class name
    const classToRemove = ['class-to-remove']; // Add any class names you want to remove to this array

    classToRemove.forEach(className => {
        const elements = body.getElementsByClassName(className);
        while (elements[0]) {
            elements[0].parentNode.removeChild(elements[0]);
        }
    });

    console.log(body.innerHTML); // Log the cleaned HTML
}

// Call the function to clean the HTML
cleanHTML();
```

This script will remove `header` and `footer` tags (or any other tags you specify in the `tagsToRemove` array) from the body of the document. You can modify the `tagsToRemove` and `classToRemove` arrays to include any other tags or classes you consider unnecessary.

Remember, this is a basic example. Depending on your specific needs, you may want to add more sophisticated logic to determine which tags are considered "unnecessary."
